| Google Faces Plagiarism Questions Over Chinese Software            |
|   from the i'll-just-take-a-look-and-yoink dept.                   |
|   posted by Zonk on Sunday April 08, @15:03 (Google)               |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/08/1824210              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]yaohua2000 writes "Google's laboratory in China has launched its first
product, a [1]Pinyin Input Method Editor. The software allows the
romanized characters to be translated to more traditional Chinese symbols
, via entering on a QWERTY keyboard. Users soon discovered that the data
Google used for the product was unusually similar to the data used by a
Chinese rival, Sogou. [2]Google has evaded the question about software
similarities, reports PC World. 'The similarities, which included an
error involving the name of a celebrity, were noted on a Google Labs
discussion board about its Pinyin IME. Users noted that entering the
Pinyin pinggong into the Google IME incorrectly produced the name of Feng
Gong, an actor and comedian.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/08/1824210

Links:
    0. http://www.yaohua2000.org/
    1. http://tools.google.com/pinyin/
    2. http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,130459-c,techindustrytrends/article.html


